article.description:
Chauncey Billups scored 30 points,
including a 15-footer with 0.3 seconds left in the second overtime, as the Pistons beat the Grizzlies.
article.headline: Billups nails game-winner; Gasol scores 32 for Grizz
article.linkText: Billups scores 30, lifts Pistons past Grizzlies in 2OT
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- It took three chances, but Chauncey Billups finally put away the Memphis Grizzlies. After missing last-second shots in regulation and the first overtime, Billups connected on a 15-footer with 0.3 seconds left Monday night to give the Detroit Pistons a 106-104 double-overtime win over the Grizzlies. "I was happy I got that opportunity again," Billups said. "We had some good chances. I know I did. I didn't get it to go at first. But you know how we do. We kept sticking around and sticking around and kept getting those chances, and I took it." Billups, who led Detroit with a season-high 30 points and nine assists, took the inbounds pass from Tayshaun Prince, dribbled to the left side of the key and hit the shot to send the Pistons to their fourth straight win. "You have to understand that (the Grizzlies) compete hard, and mental fatigue and mental mistakes happen," Pistons coach Flip Saunders said. "But we did not want them to have the ball in their hands to win the game." The Grizzlies, who lost for the fourth time in five games, had tied the game at 104 when Damon Stoudamire made a 3-pointer from the top of the key with 4.6 seconds left. Stoudamire had nine points in the second overtime. "It wasn't the result we wanted, but if you can take something from a loss, you can definitely take something from this one," Stoudamire said. Pau Gasol, who led the Grizzlies with 32 points and 13 rebounds, scored in the final seconds of regulation and the first overtime to force the extra periods. The teams were tied at 87 at the end of regulation after Gasol's basket with 7.7 seconds left pulled Memphis even. Billups' 3-point attempt with a second left hit the front of the rim and rolled off to send the game into overtime. The Pistons made only three field goals in the fourth period. Gasol scored on a dunk after Stoudamire drove the lane and dished to the Grizzlies' leading scorer with 10.9 seconds remaining in the first overtime to tie it at 93. "When they were making baskets in the fourth quarter, we knew it was going to be a grind-out game," Prince said. "I don't think anybody should have lost. Both teams made plays down the stretch." Prince added 24 points for Detroit, while Richard Hamilton scored 19. Stoudamire finished with 24 points and seven assists. Lorenzen Wright scored 14 points and Eddie Jones had 11. Shane Battier and Mike Miller each scored 10. The Pistons jumped ahead early by putting together a 13-0 run to end the first quarter, and maintained the advantage until Memphis tied the game at 79 with just over 4 minutes left after eight straight points by Miller. Detroit led in the first half by as many as 15 en route to a 48-39 advantage at halftime. The Grizzlies had nine of their 20 turnovers in the first quarter, leading to 15 Detroit points. "It's tough because I think if we played better at the beginning of the game, it might have been different," Miller said. "But give them credit. They made some big shots. We made some big shots." Memphis cut the Detroit lead under double digits on several occasions in the third period, but the Pistons maintained a 69-61 entering the fourth.

Game notes
Memphis G Bobby Jackson missed his fourth consecutive game with a right hamstring injury. Memphis coach Mike Fratello said before the game there is no timetable for Jackson's return. ... Pistons C Ben Wallace was given a technical from official Tim Donaghy midway through the third period when he argued a call. ... Memphis G Jones had four assists, giving him 2,500 in his career. ... The Grizzlies shot 52 percent from the field, compared to 41 percent for Detroit. Memphis entered the game 14-0 when outshooting its opponents. ... It was the Grizzlies' first overtime game of the season. ... Detroit became only the fourth Memphis opponent to top 100 points this season.
